their discourse and narratives to ask: What stories do settler descendants tell about their claim to belong in Kenya? How do they situate themselves vis-a-vis the colonial past and anti-colonial sentiment, phrasing and re-phrasing their memories and judgments as they seek a position they feel is ethically acceptable? McIntosh explores contradictory and diverse responses: moral double consciousness, aspirations to uplift the nation, ideological blind-spots, denials, and self-doubt as her respondents strain to defend their entitlements in the face of mounting Kenyan rhetorics of ancestry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWhite peoplezKenyaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1963.  aactivism.  aafrica.  aafrican.  aancestry.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  abritain.  aclassism.  acode switching.  acollective past.  acolonial identity.  acolonial.  acolonization.  adiversity.  aethics.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  afieldwork.  aidentity.  aideology.  aindependence.  ainternational.  akenya.  alanguage.  amemory.  amorality.  anational identity.  anationality.  aprotest.  arace.  aracism.  arhetoric.  ascandal.  asettler.  awhite kenyans.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029049540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096463140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964631/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY